Then, let us use CAPM to determine each Stock's beta. The capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{r }_{I}&={\text{Risk-Free Interest Rate + }{B}_{I}}{\text{ $\times$ Market Risk Premium}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where: 
$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{r}_{I}}& = {\text{Cost of capital for an investment}} \\
{\text{B}_{I}} &= {\text{Beta}} 
\end{aligned}$$

Now, let us compute the standard deviation of Stock I by determining the square root of the variance that we have computed in the prior step. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Standard deviation}&= {\sqrt { 0.00460275}}\\
&= {\textbf{6.78\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The standard deviation of Stock I is 6.78%.**

Now, let us compute the standard deviation of Stock II by determining the square root of the variance that we have computed in the prior step. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Standard deviation}&= {\sqrt { 0.032691}}\\
&= {\textbf{18.08\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The standard deviation of Stock II is 18.08%.**
